{{About-distinguish2|the [[Fragonard Parfumeur|Fragonard]] museum|the [[Grand Musée du Parfum]]}}

The '''Musée du Parfum''', also known as the '''Fragonard Musée du Parfum''', is a [[France|French]] private museum of [[perfume]] located at 9 rue Scribe, in the [[9th arrondissement of Paris|9th arrondissement]] of [[Paris]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://europeforvisitors.com/paris/articles/fragonard-perfume-museum.htm|title=Fragonard Perfume Museum - Paris|website=europeforvisitors.com|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref>

==History and exhibits==
[[Fragonard Parfumeur]] established the museum in 1983 within a [[Napoleon III of France|Napoleon III]] town-house built in 1860.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.linternaute.com/sortir/sorties/musee/paris-decouverte/musee-parfum.shtml|title=Le Musée du Parfum, un musée parisien à découvrir|last=|first=|date=|website=www.linternaute.com|language=French|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> Its rooms contain period furnishings and perfume exhibits, including antique [[perfume bottle]]s, containers, toiletry sets, and [[still]]s for steam [[distillation]] of perfume extracts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parisbreakfasts.blogspot.com/2008/05/le-musee-du-parfum.html|title=paris breakfasts: Le musee du parfum Fragonard|last=Parisbreakfasts|date=2008-05-21|website=paris breakfasts|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref> Displays show how perfumes are made today and present the history of perfume manufacturing and packaging. A [[perfume organ]] on display has tiers of ingredient bottles arranged around a balance used to mix fragrances.<ref name=":0" />

==See also==
* [[Théâtre-Musée des Capucines]], another Fragonard perfume museum in Paris
